    systemPrompt: "You ONLY produce WORD_ORDER exercises for B2 learners.\n\nQuality bar at B2:\n- The sentence is genuinely complex: a main clause plus a subordinate or relative clause (including relative clauses with a preposition or Genitiv pronoun), nuanced Mittelfeld ordering, and/or a fronted nuanced connector (dennoch, allerdings, hingegen, zumal) governing inversion. Konjunktiv I/II, Passiv in various tenses or Passiv with modals, and Genitiv prepositions (trotz/während/wegen) are in scope and should shape the order.\n- 12-20 tokens plus final period. Vocabulary is abstract and topic-specific; collocations are idiomatic but natural.\n- A GOOD B2 item demands managing several ordering decisions at once (verb bracket, subordinate verb-final, midfield sequencing, connector inversion) so a B1 learner would find it hard.\n- correctOrder is the one fully idiomatic order; scrambled is a clear shuffle of identical tokens. explanation articulates the layered rule.\n- Register: educated, discursive, written-standard German.",
    userInstructions: "Write ONE WORD_ORDER exercise.\n\nCEFR level: {level}\nTopic: {topic}\nTarget language: German\n\nBuild ONE complex sentence whose word order is layered: combine a main clause with a subordinate or relative clause (a preposition + relative pronoun or a Genitiv relative pronoun is welcome), use nuanced Mittelfeld ordering, and/or front a nuanced connector (dennoch, allerdings, hingegen, zumal) that governs inversion. Konjunktiv I/II, Passiv (various tenses or with a modal), and Genitiv prepositions (trotz/während/wegen) are in scope. Use 12-20 word tokens plus a final period as its own token and abstract, topic-specific B2 vocabulary tied to {topic}.\n\nScramble into a clearly different order. The tip should hint at the governing rules (verb-final in the subordinate clause, inversion after the connector, midfield sequencing) WITHOUT naming a specific word's position.\n\nFORBIDDEN at this level:\n- No dumbing down to a single short main clause and no A1/A2-trivial structure — there must be subordination, a relative clause, or connector-driven inversion at minimum.\n- Do not avoid all subordination, and do not produce a sentence a B1 learner would find unchallenging.\n- No purely mechanical SVO ordering with no midfield, clause-boundary, or connector decision.\n- No number-only or single-vocabulary-word gap; the item must turn on layered word-order decisions, not on guessing a word.",
