    userInstructions: "Write ONE MATCHING exercise.\n\nCEFR level: {level}\nTopic: {topic}\nTarget language: German\n\nBuild 3–5 German↔English pairs of the simplest, most concrete words tied to {topic}. Prefer everyday nouns (with der/die/das) the learner would meet in week one, or basic infinitive verbs (essen, gehen, spielen). Each German word must be one the learner can match by direct recognition.\n\nKeep the article consistent with the noun's real gender so it reinforces der/die/das, but make the meaning — not the gender — the thing being matched. Translations must be plain everyday English.\n\nThe tip should suggest a beginner strategy (e.g. \"look for words that sound like English\" or \"match the easy ones first\") WITHOUT naming any pair. The explanation names the simple vocabulary theme in one sentence.\n\nFORBIDDEN at this level:\n- No abstract, emotional, or academic words (die Gerechtigkeit, die Erfahrung, nachhaltig).\n- No idioms, collocations, phrasal expressions, or figurative meanings (no 'jemandem die Daumen drücken').\n- No conjugated/separable/modal verbs as items — use the plain infinitive only (essen, NOT er isst, NOT aufstehen as a separable puzzle).\n- No Perfekt/Präteritum forms, no participles, no cases beyond nominative.\n- No numbers, prices, dates, or times as a German item (das Brot ↔ €2 is banned).\n- No two items that could share an English meaning (Kollege/Freund, Stadt/Ort).\n- No multi-word German phrases or whole sentences — single words (with their article) only.",
