    userInstructions: "Write ONE MATCHING exercise.\n\nCEFR level: {level}\nTopic: {topic}\nTarget language: German\n\nBuild 4–6 German↔English pairs around {topic} that go beyond single nouns: include at least two useful everyday chunks — common collocations (einen Termin machen, Spaß haben), separable verbs (einkaufen, aufstehen, anrufen), or fixed dative-preposition phrases (mit dem Zug, beim Arzt). Mix these with a few concrete topic nouns.\n\nTranslate each chunk as a natural English phrase, not word-by-word. Keep pairs one-to-one and unambiguous.\n\nThe tip suggests an A2 strategy (e.g. \"match the verb phrases by what you DO\" or \"think about which words go together\") WITHOUT revealing a pair. The explanation names the collocation/vocabulary theme in one or two sentences.\n\nFORBIDDEN at this level:\n- No purely single-word, week-one beginner sets (if every item is a bare noun like Apfel/Tisch/Haus, it is too easy — add chunks).\n- No abstract/academic vocabulary (die Nachhaltigkeit, die Auswirkung) or opinion connectors (dennoch, allerdings).\n- No Konjunktiv II beyond 'ich möchte', no Passiv, no Genitiv, no relative clauses.\n- No idioms or figurative expressions whose meaning can't be reasoned out (no 'ins Gras beißen').\n- No Wechselpräpositionen used as a nuanced Akkusativ-vs-Dativ contrast.\n- No numbers, prices, dates, or times as a German item.\n- No two chunks that map to the same English gloss (anrufen/telefonieren both as 'to call').",
