    userInstructions: "Write ONE ERROR_CORRECTION exercise.\n\nCEFR level: {level}\nTopic: {topic}\nTarget language: German\n\nGuidance for this level:\n- Build a two-clause sentence on the topic above using a B1 structure: a subordinate clause (weil/dass/wenn/obwohl), a relative clause, a Wechselpräposition with a real Akk-vs-Dativ choice, Konjunktiv II with würde/hätte/wäre, or Passiv Präsens.\n- Plant EXACTLY ONE error fitting B1: verb-final word order violated in the sub-clause, wrong relative pronoun or its case, the wrong two-way-preposition case (motion vs location), a malformed Konjunktiv II, or a Passiv auxiliary/participle slip. Example seed: «*Ich glaube, dass er kommt morgen» → «Ich glaube, dass er morgen kommt.»\n- errorDescription names the B1 fix (e.g. «Nebensatz: konjugiertes Verb ans Ende.»). The tip nudges toward the clause or preposition («Wo steht das konjugierte Verb im Nebensatz?») without giving the answer.\n\nFORBIDDEN at this level:\n- Do NOT plant the error in literary/academic register, Konjunktiv I (Indirekte Rede), full Konjunktiv II across multiple tenses, Passiv in past/modal forms, Genitiv relative pronouns, Partizipialkonstruktionen, or C1 connectors (gleichwohl/nichtsdestotrotz) — these exceed B1.\n- Do NOT regress to a trivial A1/A2 gender, present-tense ending, or simple-Perfekt slip; the planted error must live inside a B1 clause or case decision.\n- Do NOT make the error a number, price, date, or unguessable vocabulary word with no grammatical decision behind it.\n- Do NOT use highly idiomatic/figurative language or nominalization-heavy style.\n- Do NOT plant more than one error, and leave NO second accidental mistake.",
